I'm gonna give an answer as serious as the conversation merits. I used to frequent /mlp/, would even sometimes write short stupid greentexts and even doodle stuff for some of the generals there. But I fully grasp the truth of what you're saying. That particular fandom has some cool creative people in it, some intelligent and perceptive people who are very hardcore about things like the worldbuilding the show's writers never got around to. But there are also some seriously fucked-up people in it, who are loud and obnoxious and impossible to ignore. Lots of fandoms are like that, and this one isn't immune.

One of the things that always seemed creepy, that I saw a lot in /mlp/ before I gave up on that place a few years back, was that people immediately seized on sexualizing the characters. The vast majority of characters who got speaking time onscreen in that show have big round heads, chubby bodies, and short stubby limbs. It makes them look a bit like little kids to me, almost toddlers. I am sure this was an intentional aspect of character design, because the show's creators wanted to appeal to a very specific audience, a very specific demographic, one very much not including 4chan.

It was even more creepy to me that, in addition to all the foregoing, most of the regular characters on the show who got speaking roles onscreen act like, well, kids. It's a kids show, I know, one aimed squarely at prepubescent girls. The characters mainly talk and act like nine-year-old girls. A few of them act like very clever, very astute, very precocious nine-year-old girls. Why does a big chunk of the Internet say "Mm, yeah, I wanna stick my dick in her" when they see this? The world seemed cute and comfy, with cute woobie characters that made you feel protective. There were hints of a grand sweeping past history that the fanfic people could and did fill out. Was this not enough? No. No, it was not. Pic related. And eventually it stopped being funny.
